docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump said late Wednesday that he would deliver his State of the Union address once the federal government reopens, capping a day of brinkmanship with Speaker Nancy Pelosi, who told the president that he was not welcome to deliver the speech in the House chamber while the government is partly closed.

headline.main: Trump Says He’ll Delay Speech Until After Shutdown, as Democrats Draft Border Security Plan
headline.print_headline: President Delays His State of Union Amid a Shutdown

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court said on Tuesday that it would review a New York City gun law that limits residents from transporting their guns outside their homes, its first Second Amendment case in nearly a decade and a test of the court’s approach to gun rights after the arrival of Justice Brett M. Kavanaugh in October.

headline.main: Supreme Court Will Review New York City Gun Law
headline.print_headline: Justices Accept New York Case On Gun Rights

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The five-week federal government shutdown took a significant economic toll, costing the United States economy $11 billion, with nearly a quarter of that total permanently lost, the Congressional Budget Office said on Monday.

headline.print_headline: Shutdown Dented Economic Growth, And Workers’ Faith

docs.abstract: As House and Senate negotiators met Wednesday for the first time, House Democrats detailed their vision of homeland and border security.
docs.snippet: As House and Senate negotiators met Wednesday for the first time, House Democrats detailed their vision of homeland and border security.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — One thousand new customs officers at ports of entry, imaging technology to scan every vehicle coming into the country, increased spending on the Coast Guard, Secret Service and other agencies, and new technology at mail processing facilities to find fentanyl and other opioids — but nothing for a wall at the southwestern border.

headline.main: Democrats’ Opening Offer: More Customs Officers and Technology, but No Wall
headline.print_headline: Democrats Pack Much Into First Offer, but Not What President Wants
